","about 1317":"omkring 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"omkring 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1301–":"1301–Overleden","1299–1380":"1299–1380","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1319–1406":"1319–1406","1301–Female":"1301–Overleden","1315":"1315","1301":"1301","about 1317":"circa 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"circa 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1301–":"1301–Deceased","1299–1380":"1299–1380","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1319–1406":"1319–1406","1301–Female":"1301–Deceased","1315":"1315","1301":"1301","about 1317":"about 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"about 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan was born in 1301, in England, United Kingdom. She married Roger Curzon about 1317, in Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1301–":"1301–Surnud","1299–1380":"1299–1380","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1319–1406":"1319–1406","1301–Female":"1301–Surnud","1315":"1315","1301":"1301","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"umbes 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1301–":"1301–Kuollut","1299–1380":"1299–1380","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1319–1406":"1319–1406","1301–Female":"1301–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1301":"1301","about 1317":"noin 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"noin 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1301–":"1301–Décédée","1299–1380":"1299–1380","1315–1406":"1315–1406","1319–1406":"1319–1406","1301–Female":"1301–Décédée","1315":"1315","1301":"1301","about 1317":"environ 1317","1299":"1299","Abt 1315":"environ 1315","1319":"1319","1380":"1380","1406":"1406","Kedleston, D